      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When Two-Letter Words Beat Longer Words</h2>
      <p>A common beginner mistake is always looking for the longest possible word. In reality, a well-placed two-letter word often outscores a longer one. Here's when to choose short over long:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Premium square access:</strong> QI on a triple letter square (31 points) beats most 5-letter words played on no bonus.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Parallel plays:</strong> A two-letter word that forms 3-4 crosswords simultaneously can score 30-50 points total.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Rack management:</strong> Playing ZA to dump Z keeps your rack flexible for the next turn's bingo attempt.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Endgame speed:</strong> Quick two-letter plays let you go out first, leaving your opponent holding tiles that subtract from their score.</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Use our <a href="/" class="text-blue-400 hover:underline">word finder</a> to check all available plays from your current tiles — it ranks results by score, so you can instantly see whether a two-letter word beats your longer options.</p>

